# =============================================================================
# Cinder OS — packages.list
# Minimal Debian ARM64 package manifest for Cinder OS base system
#
# Usage:
#   This file is consumed by build-image.sh during image construction.
#   Packages are installed in section order via debootstrap + chroot apt.
#
# Principles:
#   - Every package here must earn its place. If Cinder does not use it
#     directly, it should not be installed.
#   - Desktop environments, X11, sound, Bluetooth, and any GUI toolkits
#     are explicitly excluded. Cinder OS is a headless server OS.
#   - Security packages are not optional. They are listed in their own
#     section and must not be removed without a documented replacement.
#   - Package versions are not pinned here; the build script pins to the
#     Debian stable (bookworm) snapshot date recorded in build-image.sh.
#   - Comments explain WHY each package is present, not just what it is.
#     If you cannot explain why a package is here, remove it.
#
# Sections:
#   1.  Base system essentials
#   2.  Networking
#   3.  Filesystem and storage
#   4.  Java runtime
#   5.  System monitoring and diagnostics
#   6.  Security
#   7.  Cinder tooling dependencies
#   8.  Raspberry Pi 4 / ARM64 hardware support
#   9.  Build-time only (not installed in final image)
#
# Format:
#   package-name        # reason
#   # SECTION: section name
#   # EXCLUDE: package-name  # why it is explicitly excluded
#
# =============================================================================


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 1: Base system essentials
# =============================================================================
# The absolute minimum to have a functional, administrable Debian system.
# No extras. No "might be useful" packages.

base-files                  # Debian base filesystem hierarchy
base-passwd                 # /etc/passwd and /etc/group base entries
bash                        # Default shell for Cinder scripts
coreutils                   # ls, cp, mv, rm, cat, etc.
util-linux                  # mount, umount, lsblk, taskset, ionice, etc.
procps                      # ps, top, free, vmstat — used by health-check scripts
sysvinit-utils              # service command compatibility shim
systemd                     # Init system and service manager
systemd-sysv                # systemd SysV compatibility (update-rc.d etc.)
dbus                        # Required by systemd for unit communication
udev                        # Device manager — required for USB hotplug detection
login                       # login, nologin, getty
passwd                      # useradd, usermod, chpasswd
sudo                        # Admin privilege escalation for cinder-admin user
less                        # Pager for log review
nano                        # Minimal editor for on-device config editing
ca-certificates             # TLS root certificates — required for apt and Java TLS
tzdata                      # Timezone data — chunk timestamps, backup filenames
locales                     # UTF-8 locale — Java requires this for correct encoding

# EXCLUDE: vim           # Too large for a minimal image; nano covers admin needs
# EXCLUDE: emacs         # Absolutely not
# EXCLUDE: manpages      # Save space; docs are in Cinder's own docs/ directory
# EXCLUDE: info          # Same rationale as manpages


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 2: Networking
# =============================================================================
# Tools for network configuration, diagnostics, and service communication.
# Pi 4 uses the built-in gigabit Ethernet (brcmstb GENET driver).

iproute2                    # ip, ss, tc — modern network config (replaces net-tools)
iputils-ping                # ping — basic reachability test
curl                        # HTTP client — used by cinder-control health checks and update scripts
wget                        # Fallback downloader for provisioning scripts
openssl                     # TLS CLI — certificate verification, manual HTTPS tests
nftables                    # Firewall — preferred over iptables on Debian bookworm ARM64
net-tools                   # ifconfig, netstat — legacy compat; some Java tools reference these
dnsutils                    # dig, nslookup — DNS diagnostics for control node name resolution
hostname                    # Sets system hostname; referenced in Cinder Control node identity

# EXCLUDE: wicd           # Wireless daemon — no WiFi in production Pi 4 server configs
# EXCLUDE: wpasupplicant  # Same; Cinder OS targets wired Ethernet only
# EXCLUDE: avahi-daemon   # mDNS discovery not needed in server context; attack surface


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 3: Filesystem and storage
# =============================================================================
# Storage management for world data, backups, USB import, and log rotation.

e2fsprogs                   # ext4 filesystem tools — mkfs.ext4, fsck.ext4
dosfstools                  # FAT32 tools — mkfs.vfat, fsck.vfat — for USB drive support
exfatprogs                  # exFAT tools — modern exFAT (replaces exfat-fuse) for USB drives
ntfs-3g                     # NTFS support — many users format USB drives on Windows
parted                      # Partition management — used in build-image.sh
fdisk                       # Disk partitioning — used in build-image.sh
gdisk                       # GPT partition tool — for NVMe/SSD expansion path
rsync                       # Used by usb-import.sh, backup scripts, and world sync
gzip                        # Log compression — launch.sh rotates logs with gzip
xz-utils                    # xz compression — Cinder OS image compression
cpio                        # Initramfs tooling — required by kernel packaging
btrfs-progs                 # Optional btrfs support for advanced NVMe setups
smartmontools               # SMART disk health monitoring — valuable on SD cards
logrotate                   # System log rotation complement to launch.sh rotation

# EXCLUDE: lvm2          # LVM not needed on Pi 4 single-disk setups
# EXCLUDE: mdadm         # Software RAID not applicable to Pi 4 deployments
# EXCLUDE: zfsutils      # ZFS memory overhead incompatible with Pi 4 constraints


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 4: Java runtime
# =============================================================================
# Cinder Core requires Java 17+. We install 21 for ZGC availability and
# long-term support horizon.

openjdk-21-jre-headless     # Java 21 JRE, headless (no X11 dependency) — ARM64 build
                            # Provides: /usr/lib/jvm/java-21-openjdk-arm64/
                            # ~180MB installed; necessary and non-negotiable

# EXCLUDE: default-jdk             # Pulls in full JDK including compiler; not needed at runtime
# EXCLUDE: openjdk-17-jre-headless # Java 17 is minimum; we install 21 for ZGC + longevity
# EXCLUDE: openjdk-21-jdk          # Full JDK includes javac; not needed on compute node
# NOTE: If building Cinder Core on the Pi itself, add openjdk-21-jdk to the
#       BUILD section below. Production images should use JRE only.


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 5: System monitoring and diagnostics
# =============================================================================
# Tools used by Cinder Control monitoring scripts, health checks, and
# the cinder-bench measurement pipeline.

sysstat                     # sar, iostat, mpstat — used by cinder-bench for system metrics
htop                        # Interactive process viewer — admin convenience
lsof                        # List open files — used in health-check.sh to inspect JVM handles
strace                      # Syscall tracer — used for deep performance debugging
perf-tools-unstable         # Linux perf — used by cinder-bench for hardware PMU counters
                            # ARM64 Pi 4 perf support is functional (Cortex-A72 PMU)
jq                          # JSON processor — parses last-launch.json, metrics output
bc                          # Arithmetic — used in monitoring scripts for MSPT calculations
time                        # /usr/bin/time — precise timing for benchmark scripts

# EXCLUDE: valgrind       # Memory profiler; far too heavy for Pi 4 production use
# EXCLUDE: gdb            # Debugger; not appropriate for production images


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 6: Security
# =============================================================================
# Hardening and access control. Not optional.

openssh-server              # SSH access for remote administration
fail2ban                    # Brute-force protection for SSH
unattended-upgrades         # Automatic security updates (configured for security-only)
apt-listchanges             # Notifies of changelog entries on upgrade
libpam-pwquality            # Password quality enforcement
ufw                         # Uncomplicated Firewall — used alongside nftables for
                            # simple operator-facing rules
rng-tools                   # Entropy daemon — ARM64 Pi 4 benefits from hwrng seeding
                            # for Java's SecureRandom; reduces SSL handshake latency
auditd                      # Audit daemon — logs security-relevant syscalls
libcap2-bin                 # setcap — used to grant CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE to Java
                            # if Cinder Core ever binds to ports < 1024

# EXCLUDE: iptables       # Replaced by nftables on bookworm; avoid running both
# EXCLUDE: telnet         # Plaintext remote access; never appropriate
# EXCLUDE: rsh-client     # Same rationale as telnet


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 7: Cinder tooling dependencies
# =============================================================================
# Packages required by Cinder's own shell scripts (launch.sh, usb-import.sh,
# backup scripts, health-check.sh, build-image.sh).

util-linux                  # Already listed; noted here: taskset, ionice, chrt are in util-linux
cpufrequtils                # cpufreq-set, cpufreq-info — CPU governor management
                            # Used by prestart-check.sh for extreme/benchmark presets
tmux                        # Terminal multiplexer — allows admin to attach to running sessions
screen                      # Fallback multiplexer if tmux unavailable
tree                        # Directory tree display — used in import validation output
pv                          # Pipe viewer — shows progress during large backup operations
git                         # Version control — for Cinder updates pulled from source
python3                     # Python 3 runtime — used by auxiliary Cinder Control scripts
python3-pip                 # Pip — for installing Python monitoring dependencies
python3-venv                # Python virtual environments — isolates monitoring deps

# EXCLUDE: python2        # End of life; not used anywhere in Cinder
# EXCLUDE: ruby           # No Cinder tooling uses Ruby
# EXCLUDE: perl           # Minimise attack surface; only stdlib perl is tolerated
#                         # (perl-base is pulled in as a systemd dependency)


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 8: Raspberry Pi 4 / ARM64 hardware support
# =============================================================================
# Packages specific to Pi 4 hardware operation.
# The Cinder OS image targets the Raspberry Pi OS Lite (bookworm) base,
# which includes the Pi-specific kernel and firmware by default.
# These packages supplement that base for server operation.

raspi-config                # Pi configuration utility — GPIO, overclock, boot config
raspi-utils                 # vcgencmd (temperature, throttle status), raspi-gpio
firmware-brcm80211          # Broadcom WiFi firmware — included for completeness even though
                            # Cinder OS uses wired Ethernet; avoids udev log noise
rpi-eeprom                  # Pi 4 EEPROM update tool — for boot order configuration
                            # (required when migrating from SD to USB/NVMe boot)
i2c-tools                   # I2C bus utilities — useful for hardware monitoring expansion
                            # (e.g., temperature sensors, OLED status displays)

# EXCLUDE: xserver-xorg           # No display
# EXCLUDE: libraspberrypi-bin      # Legacy package; replaced by raspi-utils on bookworm
# EXCLUDE: libraspberrypi0         # Legacy runtime; conflicts with raspi-utils dependency stack
# EXCLUDE: raspberrypi-ui-mods    # No desktop
# EXCLUDE: chromium-browser       # No browser
# EXCLUDE: pulseaudio             # No audio
# EXCLUDE: bluetooth              # No Bluetooth in server context
# EXCLUDE: wpasupplicant          # No WiFi in production (already excluded above)


# =============================================================================
# SECTION 9: Build-time only
# =============================================================================
# These packages are installed in the build chroot during image construction
# but are NOT included in the final deployed image. They are removed before
# the image is compressed and written to SD card.
#
# build-image.sh installs these in a separate apt pass and purges them
# before the final image snapshot.

# BUILD_ONLY: debootstrap         # Bootstrap tool; not needed post-build
# BUILD_ONLY: qemu-user-static    # ARM64 emulation on x86 build host
# BUILD_ONLY: binfmt-support      # binfmt_misc for cross-arch chroot
# BUILD_ONLY: openjdk-21-jdk      # Full JDK for compiling Cinder Core during provisioning
# BUILD_ONLY: build-essential     # gcc, make — for any native compilation during build
# BUILD_ONLY: cmake               # If any native deps require it
# BUILD_ONLY: pkg-config          # Build dependency resolution
# BUILD_ONLY: git                 # Already in section 7; needed early in build pipeline

